I have changed the mechanism used to shorten the displayed Segment names. The original implementation used a direct character count via JavaScript:

``` javascript
if(name.length > length) {
 return name.slice(0, length).trim() + "...";
}
```

Whereas now it uses a set of CSS rules for shortening the displayed Segment names based on actual element width:

``` css
{
 max-width: 160px;
 overflow: hidden;
 text-overflow: ellipsis;
 white-space: nowrap;
}
```

The CSS rules applied, just like the JavaScript used, appears to be supported by all major browsers.
- **max-width** - [caniuse.com](http://caniuse.com/#search=max-width) | [MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/max-width) | [W3C Spec](http://www.w3.org/TR/CSS2/visudet.html#min-max-widths) (CSS2 1998 _or_ CSS2.1 2004-2011)
- **overflow** - caniuse.com | [MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/overflow) | [W3C Spec](http://www.w3.org/TR/CSS2/visufx.html#overflow) (CSS2 1998 _or_ CSS2.1 2004-2011)
- **text-overflow** - [caniuse.com](http://caniuse.com/#search=text-overflow) | [MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/text-overflow) | [W3C Spec](http://dev.w3.org/csswg/css-ui-3/#text-overflow) (CSS3 1999-2012)
- **white-space** - caniuse.com | [MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/white-space) | [W3C Spec](http://www.w3.org/TR/CSS2/text.html#white-space-prop) (CSS2 1998 _or_ CSS2.1 2004-2011)

